    pearls: ["Multimodal analgesia is the gold standard: combining agents with different mechanisms (acetaminophen + NSAID + gabapentinoid) provides superior pain relief with fewer side effects than escalating a single agent","Acetaminophen maximum dose: 4g/day in healthy adults, 2g/day in hepatic impairment, chronic alcohol use, or malnutrition; check ALL sources (combination products contain hidden acetaminophen)","NSAID GI risk mitigation: co-prescribe PPI in patients > 65, with H. pylori, prior GI bleed, or on anticoagulants/corticosteroids; misoprostol is an alternative GI protectant","Opioid-induced constipation is the one side effect for which tolerance does NOT develop -- all patients on opioids need a stimulant laxative (senna); bulk-forming laxatives are insufficient","Calculate morphine milligram equivalents (MME) when prescribing/converting opioids; > 50 MME/day requires co-prescribed naloxone; > 90 MME/day requires specialist consultation (CDC guidelines)","Respiratory rate is the most critical vital sign to monitor with opioid therapy: sedation precedes respiratory depression -- use the Pasero Opioid-Induced Sedation Scale to detect early oversedation","Neuropathic pain responds poorly to opioids and NSAIDs -- first-line agents are gabapentin, pregabalin, duloxetine, and TCAs; these should be tried before considering opioid therapy"],
